        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cross-Team Coordination on Release Trains"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A release train that spans one team is straightforward \u2014 one backlog, one Slack channel, one on-call rotation. When the train touches "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "multiple teams",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (platform, ML, product, infra, support), coordination failures become the dominant cause of missed deploys. This sub-subtopic covers the structures and tooling that keep multi-team trains coherent."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The release train coordinator role exists to resolve cross-team dependencies before they become blockers \u2014 not to manage people, but to manage information flow."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every pattern here assumes a two-week train cadence. The same mechanics scale to longer cadences by stretching the day references proportionally."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Cross-team release train dependency map showing upstream teams feeding the train and downstream consumers",
